{
  "text": "All-trans-retinoic acid (RA), the oxidized form of Vitamin A has been shown to play a role in the conversion of Tconv into FoxP3 + adaptive regulatory T cells (aTreg) and may play a critical role in iTreg stability [CITATION_1] . Although the precise molecular mechanism remains controversial, it is well accepted that the net result of combined RA/TGF-\u00df-treatment of Tconv is enhanced FoxP3 induction compared to TGF-\u00df alone. We tested if RA could induce miR-10a in T cells. RA alone or in combination with TGF-\u00df induced miR-10a (Fig. 3) . Although RA-treated GFP -(FoxP3 -) cells did express low levels of miR-10a in the absence of TGF-\u00df, the presence of TGF-\u00df synergized to maximally induce miR-10a. This effect was specific as expression of miR-16 and miR-155 was not induced (Fig. 3) . Reproducibility of this experiment is shown in Fig. S3 . In summary, RA but not TGF-\u00df alone can induce miR10a in conventional CD4",
